+# Heroes + Teams Built — and Your Leonardo Asset List
+
+## 1. Vercel — what else you can use (short version)
+
+Ranked for an idle RPG:
+- **Cron Jobs** (free, high value) — daily quest/login resets, generate daily limited items, clean up old `rate_limit` rows. Configured right in `vercel.json`.
+- **Vercel KV / Upstash Redis** — native leaderboards (sorted sets) and faster rate limiting than the DB approach. Add when you build social/competitive features.
+- **Edge Config** — sub-1ms global reads; put summon rates here to retune *without redeploying*.
+- **Vercel Blob** — S3-like storage; where you'd host Leonardo art/SVGs served from cloud.
+- Skip: Vercel Postgres (you have Neon), Edge Functions for DB stuff (node-postgres needs Node runtime), analytics for now.
+
+My pick: **add Cron** first (daily content + cleanup, trivial effort). Everything else when the matching feature arrives.
+
+---
+
+## 2. Hero Inventory + Teams — DONE and tested
+
+### Backend (tested against real Postgres)
+- **`server/api/heroes.ts`** — `list` (roster) and `summon` (count 1 or 10). Summons are **real and persisted** now, pity-backed (Epic+ guaranteed every 10, Legendary by 80). Each hero rolls class, tier, stats, **alignment + element** (for affinity) from a seed.
+- **`server/api/team.ts`** — `get` / `save` / `setActive` / `list`. Up to 5 heroes per team, positioned 0–4, one active team for battle.
+- **`database/migrations/002_teams.sql`** — `teams` + `team_members` tables.
+
+Full flow verified end-to-end: summon x10 → 10 heroes persisted (Epic pity fired) → list roster → build "Vanguard" team → set active → read back. **Security tested:** you can't put a hero you don't own on your team (rejected).
+
+### Client UI (tab-based, builds clean)
+- **HEROES screen** — a new nav button. Tabbed roster: **All / Mortal / Heroic / Angelic / Divine**. Each hero is a card showing class, rarity (color-coded), ATK/DEF/HP, and alignment/element. Summon x1 / x10 buttons up top.
+- **TEAM screen** — 5 slots. Tap an empty slot → jumps to HEROES → tap a hero to assign it → auto-saves. Filled slots show the hero's stats and a remove (x) button. Footer shows **Team Power** (total ATK/HP, member count).
+- SUMMON screen's buttons now also do real summoning (no longer cosmetic).
+
+Builds clean, runs headless without crashing, all 34 backend tests still pass.
+
+> Note: these call `/api/heroes` and `/api/team`, which need to be **deployed** (push) and the **migrations applied** before the UI shows real data. Until then the screens render empty (no crash).
+
+---
+
+## 3. What you need Leonardo to make
+
+Your game assembles characters from a **paper-doll SVG system** + uses **backdrops**. Here's the concrete art list, grouped by priority. Sizes assume your low-isometric, 32–64px sprite style (generate larger, downscale).
+
+### PRIORITY 1 — the stuff players see constantly
+**Hero class portraits / sprites** (you have 18 classes across 4 tiers). At minimum one sprite per class:
+- Mortal (6): Spearman, Archer, Swordsman, Scout, Mage, Priest
+- Heroic (5): Paladin, Spellblade, Shadow-Dancer, Beast-Master, Sage
+- Angelic (5): Seraph, Cherub, Virtue, Dominion, Archangel
+- Divine (5): Creator, Void-God, Time-Weaver, Life-Bringer, Entropy
+
+*Leonardo prompt seed:* "isometric game character sprite, [class], [tier] tier, xianxia + eldritch fantasy, clean silhouette, transparent background, 512px". Generate the divine/angelic ones with more VFX/glow, mortals plainer — it visually sells the rarity.
+
+### PRIORITY 2 — modular armor pieces (your paper-doll wants these)
+Per slot, a few variants per tier so a grunt never has a cosmic sword. 6 slots: **weapon, head, body, arms, legs, accessory**. Aim for ~3 tiers × 6 slots = 18 base pieces, expand later. These should be **separate transparent PNGs** that layer onto a base body (matches your `paper_doll` system).
+
+*Prompt seed:* "single [slot] armor piece, [common/epic/divine] tier, isometric, centered, transparent background, no character, game asset sheet".
+
+### PRIORITY 3 — element/alignment VFX overlays
+Your affinity system has 7 elements (neutral/demonic/angelic/void/celestial/abyssal/resonant). A glow/aura overlay per element makes affinity *visible* in battle:
+- 7 aura overlays (radial glow, transparent, tinted per element)
+
+### PRIORITY 4 — enemies & bosses
+- Per-chapter enemy sprites (you have 8 chapters): a grunt + an elite per chapter
+- **Shatter bosses** — your config has these as the endgame wall. 3–5 distinct Lovecraftian boss sprites (large, 1024px, lots of glow/tentacle/void motifs).
+
+### PRIORITY 5 — UI polish (nice to have)
+- Rarity frames (5: Common→Legendary) as borders for hero/item cards
+- Summon animation frames (a portal/rift opening)
+- Icons: gold, gems, EXP, the 6 armor slots
+
+### What you DON'T need Leonardo for
+- **Item/enemy names** — your `_namegen.ts` generates these deterministically.
+- **Backdrops** — you already have chapter1–8.jpg.
+- **Placeholder SVGs** — already in `client/assets/placeholders/` for everything above; Leonardo art *replaces* these one at a time, so the game works throughout.
+
+**Smallest viable art drop to make the game look real:** the 18 hero class sprites (P1) + 7 element auras (P3). That alone transforms the HEROES/TEAM screens from text cards into a real roster.
+
+---
+
+## To deploy this round
+1. Push (new endpoints + client).
+2. Apply migrations: `psql "$DATABASE_URL" -f database/migrations/001_rate_limit_pity_alignment.sql` then `002_teams.sql`.
+3. Add `heroes.ts` and `team.ts` to `vercel.json` functions (or rely on auto-detect).
+4. Rebuild client.
+
+Then HEROES → Summon x10 → build a team. It persists across restarts.
